item.title: CSS px is an Angular Measurement
item.dc:creator: yangmeyer
item.description:
The “px” unit in CSS doesn't really have anything to do with screen pixels, despite the poorly chosen name. It's actually an non-linear angular measurement.
Using this, you can work out the apparent angular widths of things in pixels quite easily. The moon from earth is about 24.3px wide, for example. The Eiffel Tower from a mile away is about 550.5px tall. That means that when you do “{ width: 24.3px }” in CSS 2.1, you're making something as wide as the moon looks to be.
item.dc:subject: css pixel

item.title: curator's ǝpoɔ
item.dc:creator: ursamajor
item.description:
I like the idea:
ᔥ if you are just passing along a link - an image found on example.com, a quote found on example.com
↬ if you are indicating a link of "indirect discovery," a story lead, or inspiration - a video found 'in a roundabout way' via example.com (so is this saying "I usually follow example.com, and they pointed the way to a story on foo.com which linked a video made by the creators of foo.com"?), more complex possibilities.
I do want to add this to my mockup of Dreamwidth bookmarking, FWIW. Though there, we're pretty good about a culture of "via" and such, at least as long as there is an "easily taggable" source to refer to. :)

item.dc:creator: charman
item.description:
Dark Patterns are User Interfaces that are designed to trick people.
Normally when you think of "bad design", you think of laziness or mistakes. These are known as design anti-patterns. Dark Patterns are different – they are not mistakes, they are carefully crafted with a solid understanding of human psychology, and they do not have the user’s interests in mind.
